  "title": "Broad CD8+ T cell cross-recognition of distinct influenza A strains in humans.",
  "journal": "Nature communications",
  "year": 2018,
  "authors": "Grant EJ, Josephs TM, Loh L, Clemens EB, Sant S, Bharadwaj M, Chen W, Rossjohn J, Gras S, Kedzierska K."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study examined TCR cross-reactivity against influenza A virus (IAV) variants in humans, focusing on two immunodominant CD8+ T-cell epitopes: the HLA-B*37:01-restricted NP338\u2013346 peptide and the HLA-A*01:01-restricted NP44\u201352 peptide. Crystal structures of wild-type and variant peptides, together with a cross-reactive TCR\u2013HLA-B37\u2013NP338 complex structure, revealed that TCR\u03b1\u03b2 clonotypes recognize distinct IAV strains through the structurally conserved conformation of the epitope variants, enabling broad CD8+ T-cell cross-recognition despite sequence mutations. This finding is significant for influenza vaccine design, as it suggests that CD8+ T-cell-targeted vaccines could provide protection across genetically divergent IAV strains, offering an advantage when vaccine strains are mismatched to circulating viruses or novel pandemic strains emerge with limited antibody-mediated immunity.",
